event_text: Kenecott Exploration Australia PL explored for copper at the Arrino prospect in the 1970s. The lack of outcrop within most of the South West Terrane, predominantly freehold farmland, acted as a disincentive for the early prospectors, who neglected the region in favour of the traditional mining areas of Southern Cross and the Eastern Goldfields where it was much easier to conduct prospecting activities with a higher chance of success. Exploration during the nickel boom of the late 1960s was constrained by the lack of airborne geophysical data at resolutions that could be used for exploration purposes. The underexplored nature of the terrain is a positive feature of the region because although the number of discovered mineral deposits is small, there are some significant examples and it is likely that more will be discovered with persistence. event_text: 2.2.2 Mapping Methodology Target generation work in the previous reporting period identified seven TEM targets at the Eastern Ultramafic prospect that were thought prospective for nickel-sulphide mineralisation. All targets were located on the dominant ultramafic formation identified in the prospect area; a thin-flow-komatiite sequence known as the Eastern Ultramafic Belt (Burke 2006b). As a result, a surface mapping exercise was conducted within the prospect area to determine the exact extents and facing of the Eastern Ultramafic Belt with view to determining the source of the anomalies. It is generally accepted that Kambalda-type, komatiite-hosted massive nickel-sulphide deposits, such as is targeted at Eastern Ultramafic, are located at or near the basal contact of the host formation. Therefore, by establishing the facing and the basal contact position of the Eastern Ultramafic Belt relative to the TEM targets, it was thought possible to determine which of the seven targets are located in geologically prospective, basal contact positions worthy of follow-up drill-testing.

event_text: 2.1 Regional Geology Yalgoo The two main greenstone sequences of the Murchison Province are both present in the Yalgoo Greenstone Belt. The Mount Farmer group consists of nine distinct volcanic centres and one sedimentary basin (Watkins and Hickman, 1990). A suite of black to glassy cherts interbedded with silicic volcanics and/or tuffs lie to the east of the Iron Stirrup ultramafic. This sequence can be traced as a continuous unit through the Project area adjacent to the Iron Stirrup ultramafic.

event_text: (Seymour, D.B et al, 1988; Powell, C. & Horwitz, R.C 1994) Powell and Horwitz (1994) proposes the subdivision of the Wyloo Group into upper and lower sub-groups based on the presence of a distinct unconformable geological boundary separating the two groups resulting from tectonic activity in the formation of the Ashburton Trough (i.e. Mount McGrath Formation unconformable overlies the Duck Creek Dolomite.) This hypothesis is supported by the locality of deposition of the sediments that comprise both the lower and upper Wyloo Groups. Sediments belonging to both the lower and upper Wyloo Groups are present only within the Mount McGrath and Ashburton Trough respectively. This geological unconformity that separates the Wyloo Group into separate upper and lower subgroups was created during the down faulting and subsidence at the latter parts of the lower Wyloo Group sedimentation in the Mount McGrath Trough, resulting from lateral tectonic extensions and the formation of the Ashburton trough.
